Class CTStringPartyOne

java.lang.Object
  edu.biu.scapi.interactiveMidProtocols.coinTossing.CTStringPartyOne
All Implemented Interfaces:
CTPartyOne, Covert, Malicious, OneSidedSimulation, ProtocolSecLevel, SecurityLevel, SemiHonest, StandAlone
public class CTStringPartyOne
extends java.lang.Object
implements CTPartyOne, StandAlone, Malicious

Concrete implementation of a protocol for tossing a string from party one's point of view.

This protocol is fully secure under the stand-alone simulation-based definitions.

This protocol is based on: Y. Lindell. Parallel Coin-Tossing and Constant-Round Secure Two-Party Computation. CRYPTO 2001.

The pseudo code of this protocol can be found in Protocol 6.2 of pseudo codes document at http://crypto.biu.ac.il/scapi/SDK_Pseudocode_SCAPI_V2.0.0.pdf.

Author:
Cryptography and Computer Security Research Group Department of Computer Science Bar-Ilan University (Moriya Farbstein)

Method Detail

toss

public CTOutput toss()
              throws java.io.IOException,
                     CheatAttemptException,
                     java.lang.ClassNotFoundException,
                     CommitValueException
Execute the following protocol:

"SAMPLE a random L-bit string s1 <- {0,1}^L

RUN subprotocol COMMIT.commit on s1

RUN the prover in a ZKPOK_FROM_SIGMA applied to a SIGMA protocol that P1 knows the committed value s1

WAIT for an L-bit string s2 from P2

SEND s1 to P2

RUN the prover in ZK_FROM_SIGMA applied to a SIGMA protocol that the committed value was s1

OUTPUT s1 XOR s2".

Specified by:
toss in interface CTPartyOne
Returns:
CTOutput contains the tossed "coin".
Throws:
java.io.IOException - can occur in the commit phase.
CheatAttemptException - if party one suspects that party two is trying to cheat.
java.lang.ClassNotFoundException - if there was a problem in the serialization mechanism
CommitValueException - can occur in case the protocol uses an ElGamal committer.
